00:05:04.816 --> 00:05:07.576
Oh, okay, yeah, like the skills. Yeah, okay.

00:05:08.236 --> 00:05:10.783
Yeah, so skills are interesting

00:05:10.836 --> 00:05:13.396
and so skills are supported in both Claude Code

00:05:13.456 --> 00:05:15.616
and outside of Claude Code as well.

00:05:15.636 --> 00:05:19.236
It's in general something that we train into our models.

00:05:19.556 --> 00:05:21.432
The idea behind skills is that

00:05:23.333 --> 00:05:24.805
there are so many different skills,

00:05:24.836 --> 00:05:26.727
it's sort of one of the things we crowdsource

00:05:26.836 --> 00:05:30.096
and so you can download skills from online.

00:05:30.136 --> 00:05:34.346
And all it is is basically just like

00:05:34.396 --> 00:05:37.856
a dynamically loaded prompt.

00:05:38.256 --> 00:05:40.227
And so someone else can write the prompt

00:05:40.296 --> 00:05:42.836
and it basically loads dynamically.

00:05:43.156 --> 00:05:45.696
In the very beginning, it only takes the top part,

00:05:45.736 --> 00:05:47.556
so the description and the name of the skill

00:05:47.716 --> 00:05:49.596
that's actually in the system prompt.

00:05:49.606 --> 00:05:51.236
And then when that's actually required,

00:05:51.616 --> 00:05:55.113
it will actually load the entire contents of the skill

00:05:55.216 --> 00:05:57.036
so you can use it as a prompt.

00:05:57.356 --> 00:05:59.592
And one thing that's interesting about skills is that

00:06:01.538 --> 00:06:04.406
in the future, I think one of the ways we think about it is

00:06:04.456 --> 00:06:08.216
that in the future,

00:06:08.556 --> 00:06:12.756
there may or may not be writing much less code.

00:06:13.256 --> 00:06:15.036
And instead of writing code,

00:06:15.716 --> 00:06:18.216
our jobs may be just to be writing prompts, right?

00:06:18.226 --> 00:06:21.746
And so skills is one way of basically allowing us

00:06:21.776 --> 00:06:23.916
to get to that world where we're focused more

00:06:23.976 --> 00:06:26.876
on writing prompts than writing code itself.

00:06:27.216 --> 00:06:28.736
And so instead of thinking about,

00:06:29.456 --> 00:06:31.796
if I need to do something, I'm just going to write code.

00:06:32.876 --> 00:06:36.277
In the future, it may become like, I need to do something,

00:06:36.296 --> 00:06:37.145
I need to build a website,

00:06:37.216 --> 00:06:41.483
I need to make a system that does billing.

00:06:41.776 --> 00:06:44.804
Instead of writing code, I just write a prompt

00:06:45.036 --> 00:06:47.096
and then the LLM will take that prompt

00:06:47.336 --> 00:06:49.236
and make working code out of it.

00:06:49.336 --> 00:06:51.516
And so I think skills in a future world

00:06:51.556 --> 00:06:53.796
where we look ahead where the models are getting better

00:06:53.836 --> 00:06:56.516
and the coding engines are getting better,

00:06:56.896 --> 00:06:58.956
it may be the case that skills are,

00:06:59.476 --> 00:07:01.636
you know, the skill and the way the prompts are packaged

00:07:01.696 --> 00:07:04.436
are like the future of how you write code.

00:07:04.456 --> 00:07:05.616
Like almost in the way

00:07:05.856 --> 00:07:09.026
like right now you use like a programming library,

00:07:09.036 --> 00:07:11.776
in the future you might just be using a skill

00:07:11.956 --> 00:07:15.827
sort of as a library rather than just actually coding

00:07:16.416 --> 00:07:17.556
in the same way you use a library

00:07:17.576 --> 00:07:19.376
