00:13:59.732 --> 00:14:02.232
instead of continuing a single conversation on and on,

00:14:02.272 --> 00:14:06.128
we usually have whenever we need to do a task

00:14:06.492 --> 00:14:07.412
that we can break down,

00:14:07.452 --> 00:14:09.812
we spin up a new Claude to do it.

00:14:10.172 --> 00:14:12.412
And we might do it in a separate worktree,

00:14:12.452 --> 00:14:13.732
which is a git worktree,

00:14:13.772 --> 00:14:16.342
which is effectively like a copy of the repo.

00:14:16.342 --> 00:14:19.526
And so instead of having one single conversation

00:14:20.222 --> 00:14:22.142
that does everything,

00:14:22.152 --> 00:14:23.612
we have multiple conversations

00:14:23.672 --> 00:14:25.930
with each with their own context

00:14:26.432 --> 00:14:29.452
that handles, that breaks down this task.

00:14:29.492 --> 00:14:30.992
And so in this way,

00:14:31.432 --> 00:14:33.192
you don't have like one single conversation

00:14:33.232 --> 00:14:36.612
with all the context that solves all your problems,

00:14:36.652 --> 00:14:38.452
because that gets harder for the model

00:14:39.632 --> 00:14:41.240
to effectively handle the context

00:14:41.652 --> 00:14:43.652
around all the different problems that you have.

00:14:43.852 --> 00:14:45.592
But instead if you have multiple Claudes,

00:14:45.672 --> 00:14:47.132
like maybe five different Claudes

00:14:47.212 --> 00:14:48.992
working on five different problems,

00:14:49.192 --> 00:14:52.492
and each one is solving its own problem,

00:14:53.352 --> 00:14:55.078
then that way you don't end up having

00:14:56.032 --> 00:14:58.988
the context between the different problems

00:14:59.612 --> 00:15:01.298
build up and affect

00:15:01.492 --> 00:15:04.872
basically the task that you're trying to solve.

00:15:05.112 --> 00:15:07.952
And so I think effectively managing

00:15:08.012 --> 00:15:09.992
different contexts

00:15:10.092 --> 00:15:12.460
and adding different Claude instances

00:15:12.852 --> 00:15:14.565
for the problem you're trying to solve

00:15:15.192 --> 00:15:16.779
allows you to basically break up

00:15:17.332 --> 00:15:19.392
and use the context wisely

00:15:19.472 --> 00:15:22.352
to just solve that unique problem

00:15:22.432 --> 00:15:23.572
rather than trying to solve

00:15:24.152 --> 00:15:26.312
a problem that's way too big for the context

00:15:26.372 --> 00:15:29.132
and having a lot of unnecessary information

00:15:29.272 --> 00:15:30.052
in the context.

00:15:37.164 --> 00:15:39.984
Any other questions for follow-up there?

00:15:40.004 --> 00:15:42.524
I'm happy to talk about it too.

00:15:43.524 --> 00:15:45.044
Hey, how's it going? Kelly.

00:15:46.344 --> 00:15:47.884
I guess my question is, first of all,

00:15:47.964 --> 00:15:51.384
I use Claude Code exclusively for my entire stack.

00:15:51.737 --> 00:15:54.254
Maybe 10% now is actually hand-written code.

00:15:55.704 --> 00:15:57.204
But my question is,

00:15:57.604 --> 00:15:59.484
I use worktrees and all that great stuff,

00:15:59.524 --> 00:16:02.989
but I would really prefer to plan on,

00:16:03.304 --> 00:16:04.524
I use the planning mode quite a bit,

00:16:04.624 --> 00:16:06.764
I prefer to plan on my computer

00:16:06.774 --> 00:16:09.004
and hand off to Claude Web.

00:16:09.554 --> 00:16:11.194
But there's no like, after you plan it's like,

00:16:11.194 --> 00:16:12.984
"Do you want to bypass?" or "Do you want to whatever?".

00:16:13.004 --> 00:16:16.324
So how do you guys handle the planning locally

00:16:16.624 --> 00:16:19.224
and pushing it to the web is my question.

00:16:19.324 --> 00:16:20.704
Or are you coming out with that feature?

00:16:20.732 --> 00:16:22.344
Because that would be nice.

00:16:22.924 --> 00:16:27.564
Yeah, I think it's something that we'll have.

00:16:28.064 --> 00:16:30.224
I need to check back with our release lead,

00:16:30.264 --> 00:16:32.876
but I think it's definitely a use case that's important

00:16:32.984 --> 00:16:35.384
that lets you push and pull from the web.

00:16:37.244 --> 00:16:38.973
Yeah, I think it's something

00:16:39.024 --> 00:16:44.864
we've definitely been exploring.

00:16:45.684 --> 00:16:50.254
That's a great call. I think you're right in that

00:16:51.524 --> 00:16:53.664
the web is going to be a huge part

00:16:53.704 --> 00:16:57.124
for basically handing work off asynchronously

00:16:57.164 --> 00:17:03.284
and not having to worry about worktrees locally.

00:17:03.284 --> 00:17:05.444
Ok. So next question from our audience

00:17:05.483 --> 00:17:07.710
from the YouTube นะครับ

00:17:08.377 --> 00:17:10.544
The first question is: Can Claude Code

00:17:10.704 --> 00:17:14.624
has context larger than 200,000 tokens?

00:17:17.404 --> 00:17:18.983
Yeah, I think that

00:17:19.112 --> 00:17:21.384
200,000 is our normal context size,

00:17:21.404 --> 00:17:24.547
but we have released sort of experimental models

00:17:25.503 --> 00:17:29.824
or with the API, like a larger context.

00:17:30.924 --> 00:17:33.586
And so we are playing around with that,

00:17:33.624 --> 00:17:35.124
it certainly is possible,

00:17:35.384 --> 00:17:36.844
but it isn't something that is

00:17:37.824 --> 00:17:40.364
in our main Claude Code for now,

00:17:40.524 --> 00:17:42.704
but we are looking into that as a possibility

00:17:43.104 --> 00:17:47.304
as some models can support larger context sizes.

00:17:47.364 --> 00:17:49.264
Ok. So the next question is

00:17:49.524 --> 00:17:53.024
how do you use multi-agents in your work?

00:17:56.436 --> 00:17:58.566
Yeah, so we use it. I think it really depends

00:17:58.576 --> 00:17:59.456
on the use case.

00:18:00.076 --> 00:18:03.086
I think as I said before, we could have

00:18:03.096 --> 00:18:04.936
basically multiple Claude instances.

00:18:05.256 --> 00:18:06.796
That's one way. And then within each

00:18:06.836 --> 00:18:08.276
Claude instance, there's also this idea

00:18:08.316 --> 00:18:09.786
of subagents.

00:18:10.156 --> 00:18:11.676
Subagents basically allow you

00:18:11.736 --> 00:18:15.636
to parallelize work.

00:18:15.798 --> 00:18:16.986
And so what that means is that,

00:18:17.016 --> 00:18:19.786
for example, one thing I think

00:18:20.456 --> 00:18:21.426
it does pretty well is like,

00:18:21.456 --> 00:18:24.396
let's say there is an issue.

00:18:24.416 --> 00:18:26.036
So there's a crash somewhere

00:18:26.636 --> 00:18:27.696
in the codebase.

00:18:28.125 --> 00:18:30.016
And I actually need to look at

00:18:30.036 --> 00:18:33.576
the past 100 different commits,

00:18:34.016 --> 00:18:35.536
to ask Claude to look at

00:18:35.576 --> 00:18:36.556
the past 100 commits

00:18:36.636 --> 00:18:39.136
to try to find out where we introduced

00:18:39.196 --> 00:18:40.176
this bug.

00:18:40.196 --> 00:18:42.476
And so that's a really common use case

00:18:42.496 --> 00:18:43.246
for subagents.

00:18:43.256 --> 00:18:44.456
And so what I usually would ask

00:18:44.503 --> 00:18:47.036
it to do is like, "Oh, hey, Claude,

00:18:47.056 --> 00:18:48.651
can you spin up like 10, 20

00:18:48.756 --> 00:18:50.326
different subagents, look through

00:18:50.356 --> 00:18:52.096
the last 100 commits,

00:18:52.196 --> 00:18:53.956
and try to find the commits that are

00:18:53.996 --> 00:18:56.646
likely to have caused this bug."

00:18:56.916 --> 00:18:58.476
And it basically goes in and it tries

00:18:58.516 --> 00:19:00.616
to look at the last 100 commits

00:19:00.636 --> 00:19:02.696
to see what potentially caused

00:19:02.756 --> 00:19:03.836
the issue.

00:19:03.856 --> 00:19:06.636
And then it might come back with like

00:19:06.796 --> 00:19:08.046
three or five possible commits.

00:19:08.456 --> 00:19:09.776
And then that way I can look into it

00:19:10.036 --> 00:19:12.276
and manually see which one

00:19:12.336 --> 00:19:14.016
potentially caused the bug.

00:19:14.059 --> 00:19:15.386
But something like that is really helpful

00:19:15.456 --> 00:19:16.336
because otherwise it would have

00:19:16.376 --> 00:19:17.996
taken me much longer to look through

00:19:18.673 --> 00:19:19.936
100 different commits myself

00:19:19.976 --> 00:19:21.566
to try to find out what could

00:19:21.576 --> 00:19:22.596
have caused it.

00:19:23.796 --> 00:19:24.896
That's one use case of subagents

00:19:24.916 --> 00:19:25.616
that's really useful.

00:19:25.716 --> 00:19:28.696
If you have easily parallelizable work

00:19:28.996 --> 00:19:29.656
that can break down,

00:19:29.676 --> 00:19:30.736
you can actually just tell Claude

00:19:30.746 --> 00:19:33.226
to spin up 10 different subagents.

00:19:33.296 --> 00:19:35.886
And the reason why it's not as good

00:19:35.916 --> 00:19:36.836
to ask Claude to look through

00:19:36.878 --> 00:19:39.136
100 commits without subagents

00:19:39.156 --> 00:19:40.426
is that if it actually looked through

00:19:40.486 --> 00:19:43.316
100 different commits by itself,

00:19:43.396 --> 00:19:44.236
it would be too much

00:19:44.256 --> 00:19:45.776
for the context to handle.

00:19:45.816 --> 00:19:47.246
And so by spinning up subagents,

00:19:47.320 --> 00:19:48.716
and each subagent taking on

00:19:49.616 --> 00:19:51.616
a handful, like 5 to 10 commits,

00:19:51.636 --> 00:19:53.816
then it wouldn't be too much.

00:19:54.636 --> 00:19:55.616
It would be basically

00:19:55.656 --> 00:19:57.106
breaking down the context again.

00:19:57.396 --> 00:19:59.306
And so each subagent will maybe

00:19:59.396 --> 00:20:01.676
identify one of the most

00:20:02.996 --> 00:20:05.856
likely causes for the crash.

00:20:06.105 --> 00:20:07.616
And then that way you'll be able

00:20:07.696 --> 00:20:10.816
to really synthesize

00:20:11.256 --> 00:20:12.896
and look through a larger set

00:20:12.976 --> 00:20:13.596
of data.

00:20:13.616 --> 00:20:15.076
And so that's a really common

00:20:15.116 --> 00:20:17.356
use case for subagents.

00:20:18.056 --> 00:20:21.596
Yeah, that would be all of our questions

00:20:21.676 --> 00:20:23.276
from the YouTube.

00:20:23.376 --> 00:20:26.276
Yeah, so I think we have

00:20:27.556 --> 00:20:28.936
the time is almost over, right?

00:20:28.956 --> 00:20:29.976
Do you want to wrap up?

00:20:31.172 --> 00:20:35.125
Speak anything to the Claude Bangkok meet up?

00:20:35.272 --> 00:20:37.052
Yeah, thanks everyone for coming.

00:20:37.092 --> 00:20:39.752
I'm really excited to hear so many enthusiasts

00:20:39.772 --> 00:20:42.392
from Claude for Claude Code.

00:20:42.672 --> 00:20:44.022
I think we're working really hard

00:20:44.052 --> 00:20:45.832
to try to get some of these features to you,

00:20:45.892 --> 00:20:48.912
like the larger context sizes,

00:20:49.372 --> 00:20:51.632
some of the better context management,

00:20:51.652 --> 00:20:55.332
including being able to, we call it internally teleport,

00:20:55.352 --> 00:20:58.312
where you basically take your current session

00:20:58.352 --> 00:21:00.012
and send it to Claude Code web.

00:21:00.252 --> 00:21:02.632
I think it's possible from the command line already.

00:21:02.912 --> 00:21:04.232
I don't know if we fully released it,

00:21:04.272 --> 00:21:06.992
but it's definitely coming up if it's not released.

00:21:07.772 --> 00:21:09.116
We're working on tons of different features

00:21:09.172 --> 00:21:11.132
and we hope that you like it.

00:21:12.952 --> 00:21:14.072
As I've said before, I think one thing

00:21:14.192 --> 00:21:16.107
that is quite important

00:21:16.172 --> 00:21:18.772
and I kind of tell a lot of people about AI

00:21:18.812 --> 00:21:22.892
is that, internally, the more I use AI,

00:21:23.332 --> 00:21:25.152
the better I got at it.

00:21:25.869 --> 00:21:27.572
Regardless of which AI agent you use,

00:21:27.612 --> 00:21:29.672
Claude Code or Cursor or Gemini or whatever,

00:21:29.772 --> 00:21:32.352
I think it is quite important.

00:21:33.442 --> 00:21:36.183
I do think very strongly that the future of coding

00:21:37.112 --> 00:21:39.382
is through AI agents

00:21:39.452 --> 00:21:41.562
because using it every day,

00:21:42.512 --> 00:21:45.379
the increase in productivity is crazy.

00:21:45.732 --> 00:21:47.732
I've been working in software for like 20 years,

00:21:47.772 --> 00:21:50.332
and so it's hard to really see a world

00:21:50.352 --> 00:21:53.552
where we kind of go back to hand coding.

00:21:53.952 --> 00:21:55.932
And so in a lot of ways,

00:21:55.972 --> 00:21:58.952
it's just to basically start learning that skill

00:21:59.092 --> 00:22:01.432
of how to use AI effectively.

00:22:02.962 --> 00:22:04.832
I love that everyone is excited about Claude Code,

00:22:04.872 --> 00:22:06.212
but I do also understand

00:22:06.252 --> 00:22:08.012
that some people like different things.

00:22:08.372 --> 00:22:12.372
But regardless, AI coding is a skill

00:22:12.392 --> 00:22:16.472
that's worth investing in is my take.

00:22:18.392 --> 00:22:19.672
Ok thank you.

00:22:20.372 --> 00:22:22.212
Yeah, thank you so much everybody.

00:22:22.232 --> 00:22:23.112
Bye, have a good day.
